This paper proposes a method for improving the performance of fully convolutional networks (FCNs) in complex scene understanding tasks such as semantic segmentation and object detection. As such, it is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper introduces a novel approach for combining global aggregation and local distribution, which involves estimating the size of each pattern at each position in the network as a per-channel mask map. This suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Furthermore, the paper discusses the use of GALD in object detection and instance segmentation, which could place it in the natural language processing (cs.CL) sub-category. Finally, the paper's use of end-to-end training and its focus on improving performance could also make it relevant to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
